README.md
     1‚Üí# debug
     7‚ÜíA tiny JavaScript debugging utility modelled after Node.js core's debugging
     8‚Üítechnique. Works in Node.js and web browsers.
     9‚Üí
    10‚Üí## Installation
    16‚Üí## Usage
    73‚Üí#### Windows command prompt notes
    75‚Üí##### CMD
    77‚ÜíOn Windows the environment variable is set using the `set` command.
    78‚Üí
    79‚Üí```cmd
    80‚Üíset DEBUG=*,-not_this
    81‚Üí```
    82‚Üí
    83‚ÜíExample:
    84‚Üí
    85‚Üí```cmd
    86‚Üíset DEBUG=* & node app.js
    87‚Üí```
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üí##### PowerShell (VS Code default)
    91‚ÜíPowerShell uses different syntax to set environment variables.
    92‚Üí
    93‚Üí```cmd
    94‚Üí$env:DEBUG = "*,-not_this"
    95‚Üí```
    96‚Üí
    97‚ÜíExample:
    98‚Üí
    99‚Üí```cmd
   100‚Üí$env:DEBUG='app';node app.js
   101‚Üí```
   102‚Üí
   103‚ÜíThen, run the program to be debugged as usual.
   104‚Üí
   105‚Üínpm script example:
   106‚Üí```js
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   110‚Üí## Namespace Colors
   116‚Üí#### Node.js
   118‚ÜíIn Node.js, colors are enabled when stderr is a TTY. You also _should_ install
   119‚Üíthe [`supports-color`](https://npmjs.org/supports-color) module alongside debug,
   120‚Üíotherwise debug will only use a small handful of basic colors.
   121‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   124‚Üí#### Web Browser
   126‚ÜíColors are also enabled on "Web Inspectors" that understand the `%c` formatting
   127‚Üíoption. These are WebKit web inspectors, Firefox ([since version
   128‚Üí31](https://hacks.mozilla.org/2014/05/editable-box-model-multiple-selection-sublime-text-keys-much-more-firefox-developer-tools-episode-31/))
   129‚Üíand the Firebug plugin for Firefox (any version).
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   134‚Üí## Millisecond diff
   145‚Üí## Conventions
   149‚Üí## Wildcards
   161‚Üí## Environment Variables
   181‚Üí## Formatters
   196‚Üí### Custom formatters
   198‚ÜíYou can add custom formatters by extending the `debug.formatters` object.
   199‚ÜíFor example, if you wanted to add support for rendering a Buffer as hex with
   200‚Üí`%h`, you could do something like:
   201‚Üí
   202‚Üí```js
   203‚Üíconst createDebug = require('debug')
   204‚ÜícreateDebug.formatters.h = (v) => {
   205‚Üí  return v.toString('hex')
   206‚Üí}
   207‚Üí
   208‚Üí// ‚Ä¶elsewhere
   209‚Üíconst debug = createDebug('foo')
   210‚Üídebug('this is hex: %h', new Buffer('hello world'))
   211‚Üí//   foo this is hex: 68656c6c6f20776f726c6421 +0ms
   212‚Üí```
   213‚Üí
